Prevention Checklist File: 
prevention-checklist.md Always use multi-factor authentication (MFA) 
turn on two-factor authentication for your university email, LinkedIn, and social media accounts because this will help too (add an additional layer of security) with protecting you from identity theft (using a password); 
always verify UPI “collect” requests—will never enter a UPI PIN to ‘get’ money, only use your UPI PIN to ‘send’/transfer out of a bank account check that the site you’re entering credentials into has an https:// URL and a padlock icon on the right side next to the URL (both will indicate the connection is encrypted); 
do not use free publicly available Wi-Fi to access your bank app or enter sensitive privacy passwords while using public or campus Wi-Fi, do so only while using your mobile data; be careful scanning QR codes—treat every QR code like a website; never scan wrap a QR code sent from a person you don’t know claiming it would ‘deposit’ money into your bank account; regularly check to see what applications on your phone and tablet have access to your camera, contacts, and microphone; turn of access to any Application that shouldn’t have access; identify potential phishing markers; i.e., email or SMS (smishing) that suggests immediate response to be tricked into a scam are examples of potential phishing scams.
